In the CSS code, the `span:hover` selector selects the span element when the user moves the mouse over it. The `color` property of the selector is used to set the color of the selected span.

To change the color of a span when the mouse hovers over it, you can use CSS. Here's an example of how you can do it:

HTML:
```html
<span class="hover-span">This is a span</span>
```

CSS:
```css
.hover-span {
  color: red;
}

.hover-span:hover {
  color: black;
}
```

Given a span in HTML, you can change its color on mouse over using CSS. Here are two ways to do it:
\begin{itemize}
\item Add a CSS class to the span when the mouse is over the span:
\end{itemize}

```css
span:hover {
  color: red;
}
```
\begin{itemize}
\item Add a CSS class to the span when the mouse is not over the span:
\end{itemize}

```css
span:not(:hover) {
  color: blue;
}
```

