Sure! Dependency injection lets you specify dependencies on other classes or objects at the point where they are needed. It helps to separate the responsibilities between classes and to allow for easy testing.

Now, in C# you can't specify the concrete type of a dependency when you're declaring it. This is because the type of a dependency is not known at the point of declaration. But you can use an interface to specify the type. So, consider this example:

\begin{code}
interface IOutputWriter {
    void Write(string message);
}

class ConsoleWriter : IOutputWriter {
    public void Write(string message) {
        Console.WriteLine(message);
    }
}

class OutputWriter {
    private readonly IOutputWriter output;

    public OutputWriter(IOutputWriter output) {
        this.output = output;
    }
}
\end{code}

Now, you can create a class that implements the interface `IOutputWriter` and pass a reference to that class to the constructor of `OutputWriter`:

\begin{code}
class ConsoleWriter : IOutputWriter {
    public void Write(string message) {
        Console.WriteLine(message);
    }
}

class Program {
    static void Main(string[] args) {
        OutputWriter writer = new OutputWriter(new ConsoleWriter());
        writer.Write("Hello, World!");
    }
}
\end{code}

When you run this program, it will output "Hello, World!" to the console.

Let's say you want to create another class that uses a different type of `IOutputWriter`, such as a class that writes messages to a file. You can do so by creating a class that implements that interface and passing a reference to it to the constructor of the `OutputWriter` class:

\begin{code}
class FileWriter : IOutputWriter {
    public void Write(string message) {
        File.AppendAllText("output.txt", message);
    }
}

class Program {
    static void Main(string[] args) {
        OutputWriter writer = new OutputWriter(new FileWriter());
        writer.Write("Hello, World!");
    }
}
\end{code}

When you run this program, it will write "Hello, World!" to the file "output.txt".

\strong{So, if you pass a reference to a class that implements an interface, you don't have to care about the details of how that class works. You just have to know that it implements the interface you specified.}

