\subsection{Natural Language Generation}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.80\linewidth]{figures/Natural_Language_Generation_Model.png}
\caption{Model architecture for a natural language generation (NLG) model.}
\label{fig:nlg_model}
\end{figure}

The natural language generation (NLG) task is the generation of natural-looking text from input (e.g. a set of facts). The NLG task is a key component of automated reasoning systems that provide narratives of reasoning processes. NLG systems have been used to generate narratives of legal opinions and reasoning processes \cite{sullivan2001narrative}, medical diagnoses \cite{shi2016automated}, and scientific papers \cite{miller2004automating}, to name a few.

In most NLG systems, each fact is used to generate a sentence. This structure is known as a "template", and is common in NLG systems. Typically, templates are generated manually by human experts. However, as explained in Section~\ref{sec:generative_modeling}, generating templates using a generative model is a more efficient way of generating text. The NLG model architecture shown in Figure~\ref{fig:nlg_model} shows this process. The NLG model is initialized with the facts, and then uses a generative model to generate the corresponding sentence templates. Then, the sentence templates are converted into a natural-looking narrative.

The generative model used in this NLG model is a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model that generates a sentence from a fact. The model is trained with a dataset of fact-sentence pairs, and generates new sentence templates using a method called "inference". Inference is essentially the process of taking the facts and generating the corresponding sentence templates.

The NLG model uses the sentence templates to generate a more natural-looking text. The model can also combine multiple sentence templates generated from the facts. For example, if the NLG model generates two sentence templates, the model can generate a single text by combining the two templates. The input facts and output text can be in different languages.

The NLG model used in this study was implemented using the NLG Toolbox \cite{nlgtoolbox2020} in MATLAB. The LSTM model used in this NLG model is described in Section~\ref{sec:lstm_model}. The NLG toolbox is a collection of pre-trained models for generating text from a variety of inputs, such as images, tables, and dataframes.

\subsection{Inference}

A generative model is not useful if it cannot be trained or used in a reasonable time. Therefore, training generative models to generate text for narratives is a slow and expensive process. However, given a pre-trained generative model, it is possible to generate new text quickly and efficiently. This process is known as "inference" \cite{goodfellow2016deep}.

Inference is the process of using a trained generative model to generate new text. Inference is used in NLG systems to generate new text from facts. For example, given a set of facts, an NLG system can generate new text using the facts.

Inference is also used in other applications. For example, given a set of images, an image captioning system can generate a caption for the images using inference. Given a set of attributes, a system can generate a product description using inference.

