The Cohen’s Kappa statistic can be used to measure the agreement between two raters, where Kappa has a value between -1 and 1. A value of 0 indicates no agreement, a value between 0 and .20 indicates slight agreement, .21 to .40 indicates moderate agreement, .41 to .60 indicates substantial agreement, .61 to .80 indicates almost perfect agreement, and 0.81 to 1 indicates perfect agreement. The calculation for Cohen’s Kappa is:

\begin{code}
Cohen’s Kappa = (a * p) - (b * q)
\end{code}

where a is the number of agreements, b is the number of disagreements, p is the total proportion of agreements and q is the total proportion of disagreements.

The 95% confidence interval can be calculated using the formula:

\begin{code}
CI = (Cohen’s Kappa +/- 1.96 * SE)
\end{code}

where the standard error (SE) is calculated as:

\begin{code}
SE = (sqrt(a * p * (1 – p) + b * q * (1 – q)) / n)
\end{code}

where n is the total number of examples.

