I would design a simple spam filter that uses the regular expressions library to detect spam. Here’s a simple code example:

\begin{code}
const spamRegex = /spam/i;
const isSpam = email => spamRegex.test(email);
\end{code}

The above code uses a regular expression to detect spam emails. A regular expression is a pattern that matches strings. The `i` flag at the end of the regular expression makes it case-insensitive (`i` stands for ‘ignore case’). In the example above, the regular expression `/spam/i` matches any string that has the word ‘spam’ in it.

We can use the regular expression in a simple function to test whether an email is spam or not:

\begin{code}
const isSpam = email => spamRegex.test(email);

const email = 'abc@gmail.com';

console.log(isSpam(email));
\end{code}

The above example shows that `isSpam` returns `true` when the email is ‘spam’, and `false` when the email is not spam.

In the real world, we have to deal with a lot of different email addresses. We can use the regular expression to detect spam emails in an array of emails:

\begin{code}
const emails = [
  'abc@gmail.com',
  'abcd@gmail.com',
  'abcd@gmail.com',
  'abc@gmail.com',
  'xyz@gmail.com',
  'spam@gmail.com'
];

const isSpam = email => spamRegex.test(email);

console.log(emails.filter(isSpam));
\end{code}

The above example prints the following output:

\begin{code}
[
  'abc@gmail.com',
  'abcd@gmail.com',
  'abcd@gmail.com',
  'xyz@gmail.com'
]
\end{code}

Similarly, we can use regular expressions to detect spam in strings of text, such as comments and reviews.

