Answer: \section{Research Your Requirements}

Most game design problems come down to one of two things, either you can't find an existing game that meets your requirements or you simply don't know the requirements yet.

\section{Requirements}

You can figure out what your requirements are by asking yourself the following four questions.

\section{What am I trying to achieve?}

This is the reason for making the game, it is the goal and overall aim.

\section{What do I require of the game?}

These are the essential elements of the game, the core gameplay components.

\section{What are the boundaries of the game?}

These are the limitations of the game, the things you know can't be done.

\section{What can I do that no one has done before?}

This is the selling point of the game, the unique quality that makes it stand out from the crowd.

\section{Requirements Checklist}

\strong{Gameplay}

\em{What do you want to do in the game?}
\begin{itemize}
\item \strong{Level progression?}.
\item \strong{Resource Management?}.
\item \strong{Combat?}.
\item \strong{Exploration?}.
\item \strong{Stealth?}.
